The '''Armenians in Bahrain''' are people of [[Armenian people|Armenian]] descent living in [[Bahrain]]. Though no concise data is available, some have estimated that there are around 10 Armenian families living in the country, predominantly in the capital [[Manama]].<ref name=Azad>{{cite web|title=Archbishop Goriun Babian meets Bahrain and Khobar Armenians|url=http://www.azad-hye.net/news/viewnews.asp?newsId=366jfl51|publisher=Azad Hye|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref>  Others state that the population is around 100 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Armenians of Bahrain|url=http://www.azad-hye.net/article/article_view.asp?re=876aah95|publisher=Azad Hye|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> They come from [[Lebanon]] and [[Syria]], attracted by the economic opportunities provided by the country.

The Armenians in Bahrain are Armenian Apostolics (Orthodox Armenians) belonging to the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] and under the jurisdiction of the [[Holy See of Cilicia]]. The [[Catholicossate of the Great House of Cilicia]] (also known as the Holy See of Cilicia) has established the "Diocese of Kuwait and the Arabian Gulf Countries" headquartered in Kuwait, but also serving the Armenians in the Persian Gulf including Bahrain.<ref name=Azad/>

The first [[Divine Liturgy|Armenian Mass]] was held on 10 December 2004, in Manama, by the [[Archbishop]] Goriun Babian who heads the [[Armenians in the United Arab Emirates|Armenian community in the UAE]].<ref name=Azad/>

