{{Infobox scholar | name = Bernard Slicher van Bath | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | fullname = Bernard Hendrik Slicher | othernames = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1910|02|12|df=yes}}<ref name="bwn">{{cite encyclopedia |first=Pim |last=Kooij |title=Slicher, Bernard Hendrik (1910-2004) |encyclopedia=[[Biografisch Woordenboek van Nederland]] |url=http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/bwn1880-2000/lemmata/bwn6/slicher |year=2013}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Leeuwarden]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2004|09|27|1910|02|12}}{{r|bwn}} | death_place = [[Ede, Netherlands|Ede]] | death_cause = | residence = | era = | region = | workplaces = | alma_mater = [[University of Amsterdam]]<ref name="bwg">{{Cite encyclopedia |first=Jan |last=Kuys |title=Bernard Hendrik Slicher van Bath |encyclopedia=Biografisch Woordenboek Gelderland |publisher=Verloren |year=2006 |url=http://www.biografischwoordenboekgelderland.nl/bio/6_Bernard_Hendrik_Slicher_van_Bath}}</ref> | thesis_title = Mensch en land in de Middeleeuwen. Bijdrage tot een geschiedenis der nederzettingen in oostelijk Nederland | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1944 | doctoral_advisor = [[Jan Romein]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | school_tradition = [[Annales school]], [[new economic history]]{{r|bwn}} | main_interests = Social history, agrarian history | principal_ideas = | major_works = ''The Agrarian History of Western Europe, A.D. 500–1850'' | awards = | influences = | influenced = | website = | footnotes = Slicher is the surname. The appended ''van Bath'' refers to Slicher's title of ''[[:nl:Ambachtsheer|ambachtsheer]]'' (lord) of [[Bath, Netherlands|Bath]], inherited from his grandfather in 1933.{{r|bwn}} }}
'''Bernard Hendrik Slicher''', since 1933 calling himself '''Slicher van Bath''', was a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[social history|social historian]], best known internationally for his 1960 work ''The agrarian history of Western Europe, AD 500–1850''{{r|bwn}} and regarded as the initiator of [[Quantitative history|quantitative]] social history in his native country.<ref name="boonstra">{{Cite journal |last1=Boonstra |first1=Onno |last2=Gales |first2=Ben |title=Quantitative social historical research in the Netherlands: past, present and future |journal=Historical Social Research |volume=9 |year=1984 |issue=2 |url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0168-ssoar-35049}}</ref>
Slicher commenced his studies in history at the [[Rijksuniversiteit Groningen]] in 1930 and moved to [[Utrecht University|Utrecht]] in 1934 where he studied under the German medievalist [[Otto Oppermann]]. Having graduated in 1936, he took an assistant position with Oppermann, typing the professor's manuscripts and maintaining his library, which brought him into contact with the journal ''[[Annales d'histoire économique et sociale]]''. Slicher van Bath then worked for some time as an archivist in [[Gelderland]], being able to avoid [[conscription]] as a former sufferer of [[polio]],{{r|bwn}} and returned to Oppermann's service in 1941. Oppermann's research interests took an ever more ideological turn toward [[national socialism]]; when he suggested, in 1942, that Slicher should research the Dutch role in the ''[[Ostsiedlung]]'', Slicher quit his job.{{r|bwn}}
During the [[World War II in the Netherlands|war time]], Slicher van Bath pursued a [[doctorate degree]], initially with Oppermann but soon with the Amsterdam-based historian [[Jan Romein]], visiting Romein at his home and later at his hiding place.{{r|bwn}} The thesis was finished in 1944, the doctorate degree awarded half a year after the end of World War II in November 1945.
Slicher van Bath finally settled in [[Wageningen University and Research Centre|Wageningen]], where he was appointed special professor{{efn|{{lang-nl|Bijzonder hoogleraar}}.}} in agrarian history and formed what was termed the "Wageningen school" of quantitative history{{r|boonstra}} (a label that Slicher vehemently rejected, not wishing to be constrained by the methods of any particular "school"{{r|bwg}}). At the request of the [[Cambridge Economic History of Europe]]'s editorial board, Slicher van Bath wrote ''The agrarian history of Western Europe, AD 500–1850'', his ''magnum opus'' (initially published in Dutch as ''De agrarische geschiedenis van West-Europa (500-1850)'', 1960).{{r|bwn}} The book got him a guest professorship at the [[University of Chicago]] (1967–68), where Slicher van Bath became interested in the methods of the [[new economic history]] and shifted his attention to the history of [[Latin America]]. The history of this continent, rather than Annales-style regional studies of the Netherlands and Western Europe, would be his primary research topic until his 1975 retirement.{{r|bwn}}
