{{original research|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox prepared food | name = Paska | image = [[File:Martiniouk Paska.JPG|250px]] | caption = Traditional Ukrainian Paska bread with a [[pysanka]] and [[willow]] switches | alternate_name = | country = European / Eurasian countries with predominant Orthodox religion | region = | creator = | course = | type = Sweet [[bread]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Milk]], [[butter]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[sugar]] | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''Paska''' (Russian, Ukrainian: '''Пáска''' "[[Easter]]", Georgian: '''პასკა''' "[[Easter]]", ultimately from {{lang-arc|פסחא}} "[[Passover]]") is a Easter bread tradition and particularly spread in countries with predominant [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] religion or cultural connections to the ancient [[Byzantine Empire]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://macknade.com/blog/festival-breads-for-easter/|title=Festival Breads for Easter - Macknade Fine Foods|work=Macknade Fine Foods|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://triblive.com/news/indiana/5955006-74/easter-orthodox-fasting|title=Orthodox traditions observed locally for Easter season|last=Delfavero|first=Gina|website=TribLIVE.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref> Paska breads are a traditional element in the easter holidays of Belarus, Ukraine, Russia, Armenia, Romania, Moldova, Georgia and parts of Bulgaria as well as the [[Assyrian–Chaldean–Syriac diaspora]]. Due to its geographical closeness, it is also widespread in Slovakia. Meanwhile it is also eaten in countries with immigrant populations from Eastern Europe such as the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom.
== Etymology and Origins == Easter is called in Russian and Ukranian languages ''па́ска'' (''páska''/''Paskha'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english-russian/easter|title=Easter {{!}} translate English to Russian: Cambridge Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref> The word is connected to ancient Greek word ''πάσκα'' (''páska'') and Georgian: ''პასკა'' (''Easter''), derived from the Orthodox believers in Byzantine Empire. The name is connected to the Jewish holiday of ''Pesach.''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1020497898|title=Silentium : and other reflections on memory, sorrow, place, and the sacred|last=Connie,|first=Braun,|publisher=Resource Publications|others=Janzen, Jean,|year=2017|isbn=9781532617928|location=Eugene, Oregon|pages=158|oclc=1020497898}}</ref>
== Traditional ingredients == Paska is made with [[milk]], [[butter]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[flour]], and [[sugar]], except in Romania, where the recipe most commonly includes sweet cream, [[cottage cheese]], and/or [[sour cream]] along with [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[sugar]], [[raisins]], and [[rum]]. An egg and water mixture is used as a glaze.
== Christian symbolism == [[File:Lob NARkult 02.JPG|thumb|Paska bread kulich in [[Belgorod Oblast]]|alt=]] The Christian faithful in many [[Eastern Christianity|Eastern Christian]] countries eat this bread during Easter. Christian symbolism is associated with features of paska type breads. The inside of paska can be a swirl of yellow and white that is said to represent the [[resurrection of Jesus]] while the white represents the [[Holy Spirit]]. Other versions include chocolate, rice, or even savoury mixtures based on cheese. A version is made with maraschino cherries added to symbolize royal jewels in honor of the resurrection of Jesus.<ref>Joan Halmo [https://books.google.com/books?id=wOJ4sLwVllEC&pg=PA43&dq=Paska+bread&lr=#PPA43,M1 ''Celebrating the church year with young children''] Liturgical Press, 1988 {{ISBN|978-0-8146-1580-5}}. 159 pages. page 43</ref>
== Eaten with other foods == [[File:PASKA2.JPG|thumb|left|Paska bread|alt=]] Paska is eaten with "hrudka", also called ''syrek'', a bland sweet custard similar to cheese made from separated eggs and milk and beets mixed with [[horseradish]] (''chren''/''hrin'') and [[kielbasa]] (in Polish) or ''kovbasa'' (in Ukrainian).
==Assyrian Paska== In Iran and the diaspora, Assyrians will eat a Paska cake on Easter, ''Ida Gura''. The tall cake is decorated with a cross on top to represent [[Calvary]], the place of Jesus' crucifixion, and surrounded with colored eggs to symbolize the people who visited Jesus during his death and were at his cross.{{cn|date=May 2016}}
==Pască== {{Infobox prepared food | name = Pască | image = [[File:Pasca.JPG|300px]] | imagesize = | caption = | alternate_name = | country = Romania, Moldova | region = | creator = | type = [[Pastry]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[sour cream]], fresh [[cheese]], [[raisin]]s, [[sugar]] | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''''Pască''''' is a traditional Romanian and Moldovan pastry.<ref>[https://dexonline.ro/definitie/Pasc%C4%83 definition of pască (in Romanian)] dexonline.ro</ref> Pască is composed with eggs, sour cream, fresh cheese like [[urdă]], [[raisin]]s and sugar, and is especially made for [[Easter]]. The word ''Pască'' come from [[Latin]], ''[[wiktionary:Pascha|Pascha]]'', meaning ''Easter''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexilogos.com/latin/gaffiot.php?p=1122|title=paryadres - Dictionnaire Gaffiot français-latin - Page 1122|website=www.lexilogos.com}}</ref>
